WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.640
Hi, my name is Caitlin Bustos. I am a data scientist and I'm so excited to be here today

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:18.559
to speak to you all about what I wish I knew before becoming a data scientist. So as a

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:26.160
scientist, I tend to hypothesize on many aspects of my life, including what my career might

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:34.080
look like. So I'm about three years into my career now and my expected trajectory looks

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:41.599
vastly different from the reality of my career. So here was my misconception about what my

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:47.919
career might look like and opposed to the reality. So within my experiences of being

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:53.419
a tutor, intern, subject matter expert, consultant, mentor, and scientist, I've definitely learned

00:00:53.419 --> 00:00:57.820
a lot of lessons along the way, of course, some of which are technical lessons like what

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:02.619
would have saved me hours of debugging or what packages I should have loaded in sooner.

00:01:02.619 --> 00:01:07.099
That's not what this talk is about today, though I'll give an honorable mention to Dockerfiler

00:01:07.099 --> 00:01:13.139
because imagine me trying to create a Dockerfile from scratch for 12 hours on a Sunday. This

00:01:13.139 --> 00:01:17.099
talk is really about the human lessons that I've learned navigating my career for the

00:01:17.099 --> 00:01:21.699
first time. And in sharing these lessons with you, I hope that no matter what role you may

00:01:21.699 --> 00:01:25.940
hold now or what stage of career that you're in, you can resonate with some of these lessons

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:31.540
or if you're an aspiring tech professional, you can take these lessons as a heads up.

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:36.459
So the first thing I learned is that success is not linear. Second, I learned the importance

00:01:36.459 --> 00:01:42.279
of exploring but also finding your focus. And thirdly, I learned to count on community.

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:47.760
So diving into the first one, success is not linear. So here's a plot of my perceived successes

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:54.639
and failures three years into my career. And if we look at this line of best fit, we

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:59.440
can see that it was not an upward trajectory and that there were several peaks and valleys

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:04.639
that I experienced. So why shouldn't we always expect an upward trajectory? Well, there are

00:02:04.639 --> 00:02:10.839
several different factors that change over time, such as external factors, such as shifting

00:02:10.839 --> 00:02:16.500
role responsibilities, emerging industry trends or changing economic conditions. And there's

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:21.800
also changing internal factors, like maybe you create new goals for yourself, your interests

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:29.699
change or develop, maybe your priorities shift. So given these changes, it's inevitable that

00:02:29.699 --> 00:02:34.699
they can also bring about challenges and some of which challenges won't always catapult

00:02:34.699 --> 00:02:40.779
you upward. So I just recommend embracing your perceived failures, knowing that there's

00:02:40.779 --> 00:02:47.500
going to be a success around the corner. Next, explore and find your focus. As a professional,

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:51.699
you need to choose a role, industry, and then the different tools and technologies you're

00:02:51.699 --> 00:02:58.699
going to use to be successful in that role. So this is an overview of what just the data

00:02:58.699 --> 00:03:02.860
science landscape may look like. There's so many different roles associated to being a

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:08.580
data science professional, several different industries you can work in, and so many tools

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:14.539
and technologies that you're likely to encounter throughout some points of your career. So

00:03:14.539 --> 00:03:21.139
given the vast number of roles, industries, and tools and technologies, there's approximately

00:03:21.139 --> 00:03:27.699
32 million combinations of choices that you're faced with considering one role, one industry

00:03:27.699 --> 00:03:33.619
and about three tools and technologies. So to deal with all of these choices, I highly

00:03:33.619 --> 00:03:39.979
recommend finding your focus. So start on something, but don't forget to explore since

00:03:39.979 --> 00:03:46.220
there are so many different directions you can go. And many skills, which are also transferable

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:53.380
that can help you go from one role to another or one industry to another. Thirdly, count

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:57.860
on community. I'm personally a part of different women in tech communities and different data

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:02.179
science communities. And throughout my engagements with these communities, I've developed a great

00:04:02.179 --> 00:04:07.300
sense of purpose solely by just showing up. Next, I've gained a great sense of connectedness

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:11.860
by being able to relate to the individuals, a part of these communities. I think you'd

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:16.500
be surprised how many people share similar stories and experiences to yourself. Next,

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:22.940
I've gained a great sense of inspiration, just being surrounded by like-minded, humble,

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:27.660
and incredibly talented individuals in the tech industry doing some really cool things.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:30.980
I want to give an honorable mention again to the data science hangout. This is where

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:39.059
I've developed my core community. And I think we've been very helpful to each other throughout

00:04:39.059 --> 00:04:44.380
all of our careers. So in summary, by embracing a nonlinear career path, finding your focus

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.899
through exploration and leveraging the community, I hope that these lessons help you thrive

00:04:48.899 --> 00:04:52.660
in your tech career. So thank you so much. Feel free to check out my website, connect

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:57.299
with me on LinkedIn. And if you want to create your own career reflection plot, the code

00:04:57.299 --> 00:05:00.940
is on GitHub for that. So thank you so much, and I hope you enjoy.

